c manipulation","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/O/N/18 Q05","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"Expand.\n\\[\n    2x(3 - x^2)\n\\]","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"recall","cmd":"simplify"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper12-Q06","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper12","qnum":6,"marks":2,"topics":["Coordinate geometry","Geometry"],"s":"3.1","d":1,"cat":"coord","topic":"Coordinates","qtype":"coordinates reading/plotting","g":"graph","src":"0580/12/O/N/18 Q06","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"Triangle $ABC$ and triangle $DEF$ are similar.\n\nFind $DE$.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find","answer":{"type":"number","suffix":"$DE = \\dots$ cm"}},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper12-Q07","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper12","qnum":7,"marks":2,"topics":["Coordinate geometry","Mensuration","Trigonometry"],"s":"3.1","d":1,"cat":"coord","topic":"Coordinates","qtype":"coordinates reading/plotting","g":"graph","src":"0580/12/O/N/18 Q07","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"The diagram shows a right-angled triangle.\n\nUse trigonometry to calculate the value of $x$.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate","answer":{"type":"number","suffix":"x = \\dots"}},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper12-Q08","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper12","qnum":8,"marks":2,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.6","d":1,"cat":"number","topic":"The four operations","qtype":"four operations","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/O/N/18 Q08","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"$T = a^2 + 4b$\n\nFind the value of $T$ when $a = 5$ and $b = 3$.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find","answer":{"type":"number","suffix":"T = \\dots"}},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper12-Q09","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper12","qnum":9,"marks":3,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.4","d":1,"cat":"number","topic":"Fractions, decimals, percentages","qtype":"fractions, decimals, percentages","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/O/N/18 Q09","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"Complete the table.\n\n\\begin{tabular}{|c|c|}\n\\hline\nFraction & Percentage \\\\\n\\hline\n$\\dfrac{1}{4}$ & =  \\\\\n\\hline\n & = 47\\% \\\\\n\\hline\n$\\dfrac{3}{5}$ & =  \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{tabular}","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"recall","cmd":"complete","texHtml":"Complete the table.\n\n<div class=\"pp-table-wrap\"><table class=\"pp-table\"><tr><th style=\"text-align:center\">Fraction</th><th style=\"text-align:center\">Percentage</th></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">$\\dfrac{1}{4}$</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">=</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\"></td><td style=\"text-align:center\">= 47\\%</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">$\\dfrac{3}{5}$</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">=</td></tr></table></div>"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper12-Q10","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper12","qnum":10,"marks":3,"topics":["Coordinate geometry","Geometry"],"s":"3.1","d":1,"cat":"coord","topic":"Coordinates","qtype":"coordinates reading/plotting","g":"graph","src":"0580/12/O/N/18 Q10","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"The scale drawing shows the positions of town $A$ and town $B$.\n\nThe scale is 1 centimetre represents 12 kilometres.\n\n(a) Work out the actual distance from town $A$ to town $B$.\n\n    \n\n(b) Measure the bearing of town $B$ from town $A$.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":2,"answer":{"type":"number","suffix":"km"}},{"label":"(b)","marks":1}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper12-Q11","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper12","qnum":11,"marks":3,"topics":["Probability"],"s":"8.3","d":1,"cat":"probability","topic":"Combined events","qtype":"combined events","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/O/N/18 Q11","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"(a) A bag contains 6 blue counters and 2 red counters only.\n\n    A counter is taken from the bag at random.\n\n    Draw an arrow ($\\downarrow$) on the probability scale to show the probability of taking\n\n    (i)  a blue counter,\n\n\n        \n\n         a yellow counter.\n\n\n        \n\n(b) Another bag contains green counters and black counters only.\n\n    A counter is taken from the bag at random.\n\n    The probability of taking a green counter is $0.64$.\n\n    Work out the probability of taking a black counter.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":1},{"label":"(b)","marks":1}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"draw"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper12-Q12","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper12","qnum":12,"marks":3,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.13","d":1,"cat":"number","topic":"Percentages","qtype":"percentages","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/O/N/18 Q12","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"Samit invests \\$1800 at a rate of 4.5\\% per year simple interest.\n\nWork out the value of his investment at the end of 4 years.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper12-Q13","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper12","qnum":13,"marks":3,"topics":["Number","Mensuration"],"s":"1.16","d":1,"cat":"number","topic":"Money","qtype":"money and currency","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/O/N/18 Q13","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"The diagram shows a conversion graph between pounds (\\pounds) and dollars (\\$).\n\nAna finds the same watch on sale in a shop and on the internet.\n\nThe shop price is \\$120.\n\nThe internet price is \\pounds 90.\n\nUse the conversion graph to find which price is lower.\n\nShow your working clearly.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find","answer":{"type":"number","suffix":"The \\dots\\ price is lower."}},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper12-Q14","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper12","qnum":14,"marks":3,"topics":["Algebra and graphs"],"s":"2.7","d":1,"cat":"algebra","topic":"Sequences","qtype":"sequences","g":"sequence","src":"0580/12/O/N/18 Q14","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"(a) The expression for the $n$th term of a sequence is $5n^2$.\n\n    Work out the third term in this sequence.\n\n    \n\n(b) These are the first five terms of a sequence.\n    \\[\n        -4 \\qquad 2 \\qquad 8 \\qquad 14 \\qquad 20\n    \\]\n\n    Find an expression for the $n$th term of this sequence.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":1},{"label":"(b)","marks":2}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper12-Q15","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper12","qnum":15,"marks":4,"topics":["Geometry","Mensuration","Statistics"],"s":"4.6","d":1,"cat":"geometry","topic":"Angles","qtype":"angle calculations","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/O/N/18 Q15","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"120 students choose what they want to do when they leave school.\n\nTheir choices are shown in the table.\n\n\\begin{tabular}{|l|c|}\n\\hline\nChoice & Number of students \\\\\n\\hline\nUniversity & 57 \\\\\n\\hline\nTraining & 45 \\\\\n\\hline\nWork & 18 \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{tabular}\nComplete the pie chart to show this information.\n\nLabel each sector clearly.","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"recall","cmd":"complete","texHtml":"120 students choose what they want to do when they leave school.\n\nTheir choices are shown in the table.\n\n<div class=\"pp-table-wrap\"><table class=\"pp-table\"><tr><th>Choice</th><th style=\"text-align:center\">Number of students</th></tr><tr><td>University</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">57</td></tr><tr><td>Training</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">45</td></tr><tr><td>Work</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">18</td></tr></table></div>\nComplete the pie chart to show this information.\n\nLabel each sector clearly."},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper12-Q16","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper12","qnum":16,"marks":4,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.3","d":1,"cat":"number","topic":"Powers and roots","qtype":"powers and roots","g":"indices","src":"0580/12/O/N/18 Q16","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"Calculate.\n\n(a) $4.1^3$\n\n    \n\n(b) $-4 - (5^2 - 2 \\times 4 \\times {-3})$\n\n    \n\n(c) $\\dfrac{4.88 - 2.36}{5.3 + 1.9}$\n\n    \n\n(d) $\\sqrt{56.25} - \\sqrt[3]{15.625}$","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":1},{"label":"(b)","marks":1},{"label":"(c)","marks":1},{"label":"(d)","marks":1}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper12-Q17","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper12","qnum":17,"marks":4,"topics":["Number"],"s":"1.1","d":1,"cat":"number","topic":"Types of number","qtype":"types of number","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/O/N/18 Q17","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"(a) Write 56 as a product of its prime factors.\n\n    \n\n(b) Find the lowest common multiple (LCM) of 56 and 42.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":2},{"label":"(b)","marks":2}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"find"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper12-Q18","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper12","qnum":18,"marks":4,"topics":["Coordinate geometry","Geometry","Mensuration"],"s":"3.1","d":1,"cat":"coord","topic":"Coordinates","qtype":"coordinates reading/plotting","g":"graph","src":"0580/12/O/N/18 Q18","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"The diagram shows a pentagon $ABCDE$.\n\n(a) **Using a straight edge and compasses only**, construct the bisector of angle $BCD$.\n\n\n(b) Draw the locus of the points inside the pentagon that are 3\\,cm from $E$.\n\n\n(c) Shade the region inside the pentagon that is\n    \\begin{itemize}\n\n(d) less than 3\\,cm from $E$\n    \\end{itemize}\n    and\n    \\begin{itemize}\n\n(e) nearer to $DC$ than to $BC$.\n    \\end{itemize}","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":2},{"label":"(b)","marks":1},{"label":"(c)","marks":0},{"label":"(d)","marks":0},{"label":"(e)","marks":1}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"recall","cmd":"draw"},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper12-Q19","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper12","qnum":19,"marks":4,"topics":["Algebra and graphs"],"s":"2.5","d":1,"cat":"algebra","topic":"Equations","qtype":"equations","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/O/N/18 Q19","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"Solve the simultaneous equations.\n\nYou must show all your working.\n\\begin{align*}\n    2x + 5y &= 60 \\\\\n    3x - 2y &= 14\n\\end{align*}","parts":[],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"solve","answer":{"type":"multiline","lines":2,"layout":"column","template":"____ x = \\dots\\n____ y = \\dots"}},{"id":"0580-2018OctNov-Paper12-Q20","paper":"2018OctNov-Paper12","qnum":20,"marks":5,"topics":["Coordinate geometry","Geometry"],"s":"3.5","d":1,"cat":"coord","topic":"Equations of linear graphs","qtype":"equation of a straight line","g":"mixed","src":"0580/12/O/N/18 Q20","year":2018,"session":"OctNov","tex":"(a) Write down the co-ordinates of point $A$.\n\n    \n\n(b) On the grid, plot point $B$ $(1, -3)$.\n\n\n(c) Find the gradient of line $L$.\n\n    \n\n(d) Find the equation of line $L$ in the form $y = mx + c$.","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":1,"answer":{"type":"number","suffix":"(\\dots, \\dots)"}},{"label":"(b)","marks":1},{"label":"(c)","marks":2},{"label":"(d)","marks":1,"answer":{"type":"number","suffix":"y = \\dots"}}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"draw"}]